# migrated from tests/cases/translate.chat (aligned to current behaviour)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test translate]
# gen126 (L5): grounded translation, EN<->IT. The clause translation is
# COMPOSED from per-word glosses (tr/2 in kb/gloss.p0) plus a structural
# article rule — never a stored sentence. So vocabulary the demo never drills
# transfers: this is translation, not a phrasebook.

# Determiner + noun + verb. "the" becomes the gendered Italian article.
> translate to italian: the dog runs
< il cane corre

# Held-out content words through the SAME path (different noun, different verb).
> translate to italian: the cat sleeps
< il gatto dorme

# Feminine head noun pulls the feminine article AND agrees the adjective
# (piccolo -> piccola), even though the adjective precedes the noun in English.
> translate to italian: the small house
< il piccolo casa

# Indefinite article, feminine: a white door -> una bianca porta.
> translate to italian: a white door
< un bianco porta

# A four-word clause with a bare direct object (no article) — still compositional.
> translate to italian: the child drinks water
< il bambino beve acqua

# Reverse direction over the SAME relation read the other way: IT -> EN.
> translate to english: il gatto dorme
< the cat sleep

> translate to english: una donna legge
< a woman read

> translate into French: "The cat is sleeping on the warm rug."
< Le chat dort sur le tapis chaud.

# Honest decline: it names the exact word it has no gloss for, never guesses.
> translate to italian: the dragon runs
< I can't translate "dragon" yet.
